}

instruction:
Overloading: multiple methods with the **same name** but different parameters.

Java picks the right one based on the arguments you pass:

```java
static int add(int a, int b) { ... }
static double add(double a, double b) { ... }
static int add(int a, int b, int c) { ... }
```

Run this — Java chooses automatically.

starter:
public class Main {
    static int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    static double add(double a, double b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    static int add(int a, int b, int c) {
        return a + b + c;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(add(3, 4));          // int version
        System.out.println(add(3.5, 4.5));      // double version
        System.out.println(add(1, 2, 3));       // three-arg version
    }
}

instruction:
With `...` (varargs), a method accepts any number of arguments as an array:

```java
static int sum(int... numbers) {
    // numbers is treated as int[]
}
```

Write a `sum` method that accepts any number of ints.

starter:
public class Main {
    // TODO: write sum(int... numbers) — accepts any number of ints
    static int sum(int... numbers) {
        int total = 0;
        for (int n : numbers) total += n;
        return total;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(sum(1, 2));
        System.out.println(sum(1, 2, 3, 4));
        System.out.println(sum(10, 20, 30, 40, 50));
    }
}

instruction:
Return as soon as you have the answer — no need to reach the end:

```java
static boolean isEven(int n) {
    if (n % 2 == 0) return true;
    return false; // or just: return n % 2 == 0;
}
```

Write `isPrime(int n)` that returns early when it finds a factor.

starter:
public class Main {
    // TODO: write isPrime(int n) — return true if n is prime
    static boolean isPrime(int n) {
        if (n < 2) return false;
        for (int i = 2; i * i <= n; i++) {
            if (n % i == 0) return false;
        }
        return true;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] test = {1, 2, 7, 10, 13, 15, 17};
        for (int n : test) {
            System.out.println(n + ": " + isPrime(n));
        }
    }
}

public class Main {
    static long factorial(int n) {
        if (n <= 1) return 1;            // base case
        return n * factorial(n - 1);     // recursive case
    }

    static int fibonacci(int n) {
        if (n <= 1) return n;            // base cases: fib(0)=0, fib(1)=1
        return fibonacci(n-1) + fibonacci(n-2);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(factorial(5));
        System.out.println(factorial(10));

        for (int i = 0; i <= 8; i++) {
            System.out.print(fibonacci(i) + " ");
        }
        System.out.println();
    }
}
